[Re: Canine distemper, wildlife - USA (03): (CA) desert kit fox 20120203.1031833]
-------------------------------------------------------
The concern over whether coyote urine is the source of canine distemper in the current outbreak of desert kit foxes is likely to be overstated.

As was noted in a posting, materials such as coyote urine are registered with the EPA. A requirement of the registration process is that the manufacturer provides data that show that the process of producing the final product is capable of significantly reducing the pathogen load that might be contained in the raw material. Frequently, the virus used to assess this process is canine parvovirus. For those actually aware of stability of viruses in the environment, their choice would be this agent. A 5-6 log reduction in canine parvovirus in the manufacturing process would almost certainly eliminate canine distemper virus. I would suggest focusing the effort to identify the source of canine distemper virus in this instance on a more plausible culprit.

--
Dr. Edward J. Dubovi
Animal Health Diagnostic Center
Director - Virology Section
College of Veterinary Medicine at Cornell
Ithaca, NY 14853
<ejd5@cornell.edu>

[Thanks to Dr Dubovi for pointing out this EPA requirement. - Mod.PMB]

