[Re: Canine distemper, wildlife - USA (03): (CA) desert kit fox 20120203.1031833]
-------------------------------------------------------
Some points to consider in this ongoing discussion. According to Craig Greene in "Infectious Diseases of the Dog and Cat":
"CDV is susceptible to UV light, although protein or antioxidants help to protect it from inactivation. Extremely susceptible to heat and drying, CDV is destroyed by temperatures greater than 50 to 60 degrees Celsius for 30 minutes. In removed tissues it survives for at least an hour at 37 degrees C and for 3 hours at (room temperature) 27 degrees C. In warm climates, CDV does not persist in kennels after infected dogs have been removed. Storage and survival times of CDV are longer at colder temperatures. At near-freezing (0-4 degrees C), it survives in the environment for weeks."

It seems unlikely that commercially prepared coyote urine products could be implicated in the transmission of this virus into the desert kit fox population. Once introduced, canine distemper virus transmits easily within any young, naive and unvaccinated population. I would look closely at the companion animals which may have been brought into the construction sites of this solar project.

--
Allan Drusys
<ADrusys@rivcocha.org>

[Thanks to Allan Drusys for his comment. - Mod.PMB]
